#### GROUP-BY Rollup()
```SQL
SELECT
	category_id,
	product_name,
	count(*),
	min(price) as lowest_price,
	max(price) as max_price,
	avg(price) as avg_price
FROM inventory.products
GROUP BY  ROLLUP (category_id, product_name)
ORDER BY category_id, product_name;
```

It is a subclause of the `GROUP BY` clause used to generate multiple levels of summary data, including subtootals and grand total. Within a single query.


#### GROUP BY CUBE
It returns all possible combinations of groups when you are using multiple GROUP BY columns. This is usefull when your data can be segmented into different groups, but those groups don't necessarily  have a relationship to one another.

```SQL
SELECT
	category_id,
	size,
	count(*),
	min(price) as lowest_price,
	max(price) as max_price,
	avg(price) as avg_price
FROM inventory.products
GROUP BY  CUBE (category_id, size)
ORDER BY category_id, size;

-- Cube is giving us 4 different query all at once. it returns all possible combination in a sigle result
```


#### FILTER
```SQL
SELECT category_id,
	count(*) as count_all,
	avg(price) as average_price,
	-- Small product size <= 16oz
	count(*) filter(where size <= 16) as count_small,
	AVG(price) filter(where size <=16 ) as avg_price_small,
	-- Big product size > 16
	count(*) filter(where size > 16) as count_big,
	AVG(price)filter (where size > 16) as avg_price_big
FROM inventory.products
GROUP BY (category_id)
order by category_id;
